      <Abstract xml:lang="en">Dynamics of a polymer melt can be quantitatively understood by analyzing the motion of a single polymer chain in the melt ? commonly referred to as ?tagged chain?. Unlike a single chain in isolation, a tagged chain in a dense polymer system has to interact with the surrounding chains. Beyond the scale of the ?entanglement length? Ne, which is typically at least of order 100 backbone units even for a melt, it is widely recognized that topological constraints dramatically change the relaxation times of melts when the chain length exceeds about 3Ne. Melts of chains of lengths sinificantly smaller than Ne are called unentangled melts, and those of chains of lengths sinificantly larger than Ne are called entangled melts. Despite decades of reserch into both types of melts, many fundamental questions remain unanswered. The primary reason is that the slow dynamics of melts that makes access to reliable data, both in laboratory and in silico experiments, a difficult pursuit. The applicant has recently made quite some progress with in silico experiments on both of these issues, which he wants to build upon. A by-product of this line of research is that the methods developed are very often found useful for other types of polymeric systems, such as semiflexible polymers and polymer networks. The applicant has built a history on research in polymeric systems, which is expected to continue for the coming years.</Abstract>
